1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:11,200
[music] At night, around one in the morning, in a small provincial town with no particular name, a young man of about 27 or so

2
00:00:12,059 --> 00:00:19,280
walks into a solitary wooden annex in the courtyard, to visit a civil engineer sitting on a sofa with a latticed back

3
00:00:19,280 --> 00:00:30,239
and hard leather cushions, and almost immediately notices an untouched boiled chicken on a plate by the window. My name is Armen

4
00:00:30,239 --> 00:00:38,200
Zakharyan, this is Armen and Fyodor’s literary channel, and today we’re launching a new segment: “Episode.” In it, each time, we’ll carefully

5
00:00:38,200 --> 00:00:46,600
examine a single fragment from world literature and figure out why this episode is special and how what we call art

6
00:00:46,600 --> 00:00:54,980
works within it. For our first attempt, we’ve chosen one of the most chilling, yet fascinating,

7
00:00:54,980 --> 00:01:04,720
scenes from Dostoevsky’s novel The Devils. It’s an episode nearly at the very end of the book, from its concluding part. There, a certain Verkhovensky

8
00:01:04,720 --> 00:01:14,260
comes at night to the home of a certain Kirillov and sees a boiled chicken with rice on the windowsill. And though there’s a loaded

9
00:01:14,260 --> 00:01:22,459
pistol lying right next to the chicken, it’s not the pistol but the chicken that serves, in this scene, as the Chekhovian gun, which is about to go off. However,

10
00:01:22,459 --> 00:01:32,540
to understand what this "shot" is, and at whom it’s aimed, we first need to figure out who these two are and how they ended up here, in the same room

11
00:01:32,540 --> 00:01:40,640
at night, in the annex. Interestingly, even at the very beginning of the novel, as we’re just being introduced to the characters, Dostoevsky already lays

12
00:01:40,640 --> 00:01:50,100
the groundwork for their eerie night encounter. Kirillov—he is a young man, around 27; Verkhovensky, almost symmetrically, a young

13
00:01:51,600 --> 00:02:00,919
man, about 27 or so. This pointed similarity, of course, only accentuates how deep their differences lie. Kirillov is

14
00:02:00,919 --> 00:02:09,340
a vivid representative of Dostoevsky’s famous string of fanatic heroes—heroes who become obsessed with an idea

15
00:02:09,899 --> 00:02:18,660
and begin to serve that idea, to live for it alone. Only, Kirillov’s plan is different: in the name of his idea, he intends to die. Kirillov

16
00:02:18,660 --> 00:02:28,039
is obsessed with the thought of “the man-god.” He comes to this through a problem that the literature of the second half of the 19th century

17
00:02:28,039 --> 00:02:38,380
often tried to solve: how is one to live after rejecting God? Suppose God is no longer there. Suppose we no longer believe in Him,

18
00:02:38,380 --> 00:02:45,480
We’ve, as Verkhovensky might put it, “decommissioned” him. And yet, the need to fill the void left in his place—it remains.

19
00:02:45,480 --> 00:02:54,900
And while another Dostoevsky character, also in The Devils, says, “If there is no God, then what kind of captain am I after that?” Kirillov says,

20
00:02:55,019 --> 00:03:05,920
“If there is no God, then I can take His place.” Remember Grebenshchikov sang, “You feel the draft because that place is vacant.”

21
00:03:06,500 --> 00:03:16,000
Kirillov feels that very draft, and he formulates a terrifying, mad idea, with which he then falls in love: if

22
00:03:15,659 --> 00:03:24,160
a person, he says, dares to affirm his will—to leave life not out of anger, nor fear, nor rage, but solely and precisely because

23
00:03:24,160 --> 00:03:33,259
he has the right, then, Kirillov reasons, with this act he will transform all of humanity and himself become the man-god.

24
00:03:34,379 --> 00:03:44,200
“But there have already been millions of suicides,” they tell him. “Not for that,” Kirillov replies; “all from fear, not for that!” And this

25
00:03:44,200 --> 00:03:53,599
mad approach of his uncannily resembles an episode from Don Quixote. Remember, when the audacious hidalgo tells Sancho

26
00:03:53,599 --> 00:04:02,620
he plans to imitate the great knights of the past and go mad? The pragmatic Sancho then asks, “But, sir, do you have a reason to go mad? What’s the reason?”

27
00:04:02,620 --> 00:04:11,780
“That’s the whole point,” Don Quixote replies. “That’s exactly what’s unusual about my venture: who ever heard of a knight going mad for a reason?

28
00:04:11,780 --> 00:04:19,600
Let there be no gratefulness nor reward involved; the trick is to go mad for no reason at all.”

29
00:04:19,600 --> 00:04:24,760
And as we’ll soon see, these echoes in the words of Kirillov and Quixote are not accidental in the least.

30
00:04:26,340 --> 00:04:35,300
So, to carry out his mad idea, Kirillov has a loaded revolver lying by the window, next to the chicken. You may ask, why is he waiting, then? Why isn’t he

31
00:04:36,180 --> 00:04:44,980
carrying out his intention if, in fact, he needs no external reason? This is where his nighttime visitor comes into play:

32
00:04:44,980 --> 00:04:52,599
the revolutionary and nihilist Pyotr Stepanovich Verkhovensky—a completely different sort of character, a fascinating hero, both ridiculous and terrifying,

33
00:04:52,599 --> 00:05:02,880
comic and parodic, terrifyingly talkative and theatrical, but at the same time horrifying because he’s ready for any evil. Verkhovensky

34
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:12,659
comic and parodic, terrifyingly talkative and theatrical, but at the same time horrifying because he’s ready for any evil. Verkhovensky

35
00:05:02,880 --> 00:05:12,659
comic and parodic, terrifyingly talkative and theatrical, but at the same time horrifying because he’s ready for any evil. Verkhovensky

36
00:05:12,659 --> 00:05:21,500
in a way, is reminiscent of Mephistopheles, though Mephistopheles had a better sense of humor, and being older and more experienced in life, he was more modest. However, what matters is that they both

37
00:05:21,500 --> 00:05:28,080
are ultimately divided: Verkhovensky is a thoroughly practical man.

38
00:05:28,080 --> 00:05:36,420
He believes the ends justify any means. Upon hearing about Kirillov’s project of ideological suicide, Verkhovensky

39
00:05:36,420 --> 00:05:46,100
immediately devises how this can be put to good use—not to transform humanity; he doesn’t care a bit about that,

40
00:05:46,100 --> 00:05:54,780
but for his own devilish plan. He decides to commit a political murder, and since Kirillov absolutely doesn’t care how or when to die,

41
00:05:54,780 --> 00:06:03,020
he asks Kirillov, before his suicide, to write a confession to this murder; in other words, to use Kirillov’s death as

42
00:06:03,020 --> 00:06:11,820
an alibi for his own crime. So, that’s the situation at the time of their night meeting: a conflict between the spiritual—albeit sick—

43
00:06:11,820 --> 00:06:21,039
but spiritual Don Quixote was also insane—and the material, between the elevated and the base, between the tragic and the pragmatic.

44
00:06:21,039 --> 00:06:31,999
But how to show all this through a single image? Through the chicken. As often with Dostoevsky, the episode unfolds

45
00:06:32,580 --> 00:06:40,060
rapidly: Verkhovensky has barely walked in, has just clarified, “Well, our intention is firm, I hope we’re not backing out of the suicide?”

46
00:06:40,060 --> 00:06:50,899
“We’ll sign the paper.” And then, almost without a pause, he says, “Ah, I notice something there on the window. On the plate.” He walks over: “Oh! Boiled chicken

47
00:06:50,899 --> 00:07:01,020
with rice. But why is it still untouched? So we’re in that frame of mind where even chicken—” Kirillov interrupts,

48
00:07:01,020 --> 00:07:12,700
“It’s none of your business, be quiet.” “Oh, of course, and it makes no difference, but for me it does now. Imagine, I’ve hardly dined today, so if this chicken,

49
00:07:12,700 --> 00:07:23,540
as I suppose, is not needed any more—” Note how Kirillov phrases his reply:

50
00:07:23,540 --> 00:07:34,740
“Eat it, if you can.” Verkhovensky can. More than can—for himself and for someone else. “Thank you,” he says, “and tea afterwards too,”

51
00:07:34,740 --> 00:07:44,520
and what follows is even more chilling, the cherry on top of the scene: Verkhovensky instantly makes himself comfortable at the table at the far end

52
00:07:43,740 --> 00:07:52,980
of the sofa, and with extreme greed throws himself at the dish, but at the same time, every moment watches his victim. Kirillov, with furious

53
00:07:52,980 --> 00:08:03,100
disgust, stares at him motionless, as if unable to tear himself away. Verkhovensky here is the triumph of the flesh—he eats greedily,

54
00:08:03,100 --> 00:08:12,380
with appetite, with relish—for the man sitting a meter away is about to shoot himself, which means the chicken, too, is vacated. Notice: in this

55
00:08:12,380 --> 00:08:21,880
one paragraph, Verkhovensky takes away from Kirillov everything: his freedom, his last will, his last meal, and at last,

56
00:08:21,900 --> 00:08:30,759
his life. The chicken is, of course, only a metaphor, because in truth, Verkhovensky is a cannibal: people are only expendable

57
00:08:30,759 --> 00:08:41,319
material to feed his pitiful ambitions and dreadful plans. Does mankind’s happiness justify a single tear of a child? Ivan Karamazov asks.

58
00:08:41,319 --> 00:08:55,279
“And is the child with a garnish, or just by itself?” Pyotr clarifies. And Kirillov, this strange Kirillov—with his mad idea, but still

59
00:08:55,279 --> 00:09:03,480
not an evil heart—cannot tear his gaze away. He watches in terror as Verkhovensky devours the chicken, because it is not only

60
00:09:03,480 --> 00:09:13,859
the chicken he devours, but Kirillov himself—he is about to eat him. “Barabek gobbled forty men, a cow, an ox, a crooked butcher,

61
00:09:13,859 --> 00:09:24,540
a cart, a hoop, a broom, a poker—he ate the chicken with garnish, finished with this world,” and all this tangle of contradictions, fears,

62
00:09:24,839 --> 00:09:35,659
and fates, Dostoevsky shows in a single supper scene, through one plate of cold chicken with rice. The eloquent horror of this

63
00:09:35,659 --> 00:09:43,260
gastronomic scene was brilliantly captured in the legendary production of The Devils at St. Petersburg’s Maly Drama Theatre, in

64
00:09:43,260 --> 00:09:51,580
Lev Dodin’s six-hour play, staged for nearly thirty years. Those lucky enough to see it

65
00:09:51,580 --> 00:10:00,980
surely remember Verkhovensky’s chicken scene. See it once live—it’s unforgettable. Here’s a fragment of how

66
00:10:00,980 --> 00:10:33,460
this scene was played. This illustration, really, could have ended our discussion of today’s fragment, if not for

67
00:10:33,460 --> 00:10:41,640
one detail: this opposition—refusal of food, gluttony as a metaphor for values conflict—can also be found

68
00:10:41,640 --> 00:10:50,440
in a book Dostoevsky loved deeply, a book which influenced all his major works, a book which he said was the deepest and strongest in all the world,

69
00:10:50,440 --> 00:11:00,240
and which we’ve mentioned today, of course—Cervantes's Don Quixote.

70
00:11:00,240 --> 00:11:08,779
Remember how the relationship between Don Quixote and Sancho Panza is built in the first part—we spoke of it in one of the early episodes

71
00:11:08,779 --> 00:11:17,020
of Armen and Fyodor devoted to this novel. Sancho is obsessed with food: he constantly reminds Quixote about eating; at every opportunity,

72
00:11:16,800 --> 00:11:24,599
he strives to get his fill, regardless of what his master is experiencing at the moment—whether he preaches, fasts, or

73
00:11:24,599 --> 00:11:33,220
suffers. And the great American director Orson Welles, in his Don Quixote— which, by a strange coincidence, would be released almost

74
00:11:33,480 --> 00:11:43,359
alongside Dodin’s production—depicts a scene uncannily similar to that episode from The Devils: there, Sancho Panza, before the fasting Quixote’s very eyes,

75
00:11:43,359 --> 00:12:06,440
will greedily devour—what do you think?—of course, a chicken. [music] [music]

76
00:12:15,480 --> 00:12:31,359
I want this... that Marina will go… One can only clarify that in the spirit of Cervantes’s Don Quixote, this episode is true;

77
00:12:31,359 --> 00:12:38,580
in the letter, not entirely—in the text of the novel, there was no such scene with a chicken exactly like this one.

78
00:12:38,580 --> 00:12:50,279
However, this is easily explained: Cervantes didn’t read Dostoevsky, unlike Orson Welles. This is Armen and Fyodor’s literary channel,

79
00:12:50,279 --> 00:12:59,260
and the “Episode” segment. I hope our experiment with this new laconic format was a success, and if so, please write

80
00:12:59,260 --> 00:13:08,960
in the comments which other episodes you’d like to see in this segment in the future. For now, that’s it. My name is Armen Zakharyan,

81
00:13:08,760 --> 00:13:12,490
until next time. [music]